# Security headers for the deployed dashboard (Netlify / Cloudflare Pages
# `_headers` format — Vite copies this file from public/ to the dist root). If you
# deploy behind nginx/Caddy/other, translate these into that layer's header
# config. These apply to the BUILT site only, never the Vite dev server, so HMR is
# unaffected.
#
# The CSP is the main mitigation for the localStorage-token XSS exposure (see
# src/lib/auth-tokens.ts): `connect-src 'self'` stops a script from exfiltrating
# tokens to a third-party origin, and `script-src 'self'` blocks injected/inline
# scripts. The production API is a SEPARATE origin (https://api.quikfill.io — the
# app is hosted at app.quikfill.io on Cloudflare Pages), so it is allowed in
# `connect-src` below. Keep that origin in sync with `VITE_QF_API_BASE_URL`.
/*
  Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'self'; script-src 'self'; style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline' https://fonts.googleapis.com; font-src 'self' https://fonts.gstatic.com; img-src 'self' data:; connect-src 'self' https://api.quikfill.io; object-src 'none'; base-uri 'self'; frame-ancestors 'none'; form-action 'self'
  X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff
  Referrer-Policy: strict-origin-when-cross-origin
  X-Frame-Options: DENY
  Permissions-Policy: geolocation=(), camera=(), microphone=(), payment=()
  Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=63072000; includeSubDomains; preload

# The extension zip is version-stamped (quikfill-extension-<version>.zip, see
# scripts/deploy-chrome.mjs) so each build has a unique, immutable URL — cache it
# hard. The version manifest (extension.json) keeps a FIXED name and is rewritten
# on every deploy, so it must revalidate so the Setup page always discovers the
# newest build (the download link also appends ?v=<version> as a second buster).
/quikfill-extension-*.zip
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable
/extension.json
  Cache-Control: no-cache
